n occupation of Britain and in the Middle Ages it was a center for the manufacture of cloth, including the famous вАШLincoln greenвАЩ.","African American: adoption of the surname in 1 above, in honor of Abraham Lincoln, the 16th president of the US, who abolished slavery.","History: Abraham Lincoln (1809вАУ65), 16th president of the US, was the son of an illiterate laborer, descended from Samuel Lincoln, who had emigrated from England to MA in 1637."],"variants":[{"name":"Linkins","meanings":["English: variant of <b>Linkin</b>, which itself is a form of   Lincoln  , prevalent in Kent."]},{"name":"Lindsay","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name from Lindsey in Lincolnshire, England. This is first found in the form <i>Lindissi</i>, apparently a derivative of the British name of   Lincoln  . To this was later added the Old English element <i>ƒУg</i> вАШislandвАЩ, since the place was virtually cut off by the surrounding fenland. The surname was taken to Scotland at an early date and is the name of an important and powerful Scottish family.","Irish: adopted as an equivalent ofvarious Gaelic names (see   Lindsey  )."]}]},{"name":"Picot","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names ¬© Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Pierre, Francois, Jacques, Jeanpaul, Luc, Pascal, Yves.  Spanish Esperanza, Aida, Alicia, Ana, Felipe, Luis.","French: from Old French <i>picot</i> вАШpointed object, pickaxeвАЩ, a nickname for someone who used such an implement. This surname is also found in Haiti.","Catalan: nickname from Valencian dialect <i>picot</i> вАШ(sheep or goat) bellвАЩ."],"variants":[{"name":"Pickett","meanings":["English:","from the Middle English, Old French personal name <i>Picot</i>, <i>Pigot</i>, a pet form of <i>Pic</i> (see   Pike   6). In Middle English, the form <i>Piket</i> (Old French <i>Picquet</i>) was also common.","sometimes a late development of   Pickard   1 or 2."]},{"name":"Picotte","meanings":["